m","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Noel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Normand, Antoine, Jacques, Alphonse, Leonce, Lucien, Marcel, Damien, Emile, Francois.","French and Walloon (<b>Noël</b>); English: from the Old French personal name <i>Noël</i>, Middle English <i>Noel</i>, from Old French <i>no(u)el</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis (dies)</i> ‘birthday’), used for someone born during the Christmas period. Alternatively, a nickname for someone who had some special connection with the Christmas season, such as owing the particular feudal duty of providing a yule-log to the lord of the manor, or having given a memorable performance as the Lord of Misrule. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium. Compare   Christmas   and   Newell  .","English: sometimes a post-medieval variant of <b>Knowle</b> and   Knoll   (see   Knowles  ). The loss of /k/ before /n/ is known in everyday speech by the 17th century and may have been earlier."],"variants":[{"name":"Nowell","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Noel  ,   Knowles  , or   Newell  ."]},{"name":"Christmas","meanings":["English (southeastern): nickname from Middle English <i>Criste(s)masse</i>, <i>-messe</i> ‘Christmas Day’, also ‘the Christmas season’, perhaps for someone who was born at Christmas or one who played the part of the King of Christmas in Yuletide games. The name was also established in County Waterford, Ireland, in 1622.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French <b>Noël</b> (see   Noel  )."]},{"name":"Nadal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Miguel, Francisco, Jose, Luis, Caridad, Digna, Jaime, Juan, Juan Carlos, Manuel, Otilio.","Catalan and French (Occitan): from the personal name <i>Nadal</i>, from <i>nadal</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis</i> ‘birthday’), the name given to a child born on that day or during that time of year. Compare   Noel  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Noel was born about 1419, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Noell De Hilcott, was 124 and her mother, Jane Sounde, was 41. She married Thomas Chetwode about 1439, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1419–Deceased":"umbes 1419–Surnud","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1415–1485":"1415–1485","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1415":"1415","Abt 1419":"umbes 1419","1497":"1497","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1296":"1296","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","       1418":"1418","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1419–Deceased":"noin 1419–Kuollut","1419–Female":"1419–Kuollut","1415–1485":"1415–1485","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1415":"1415","Abt 1419":"noin 1419","1497":"1497","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1296":"1296","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","       1418":"1418","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1419–Deceased":"environ 1419–Décédée","1419–Female":"1419–Décédée","1415–1485":"1415–1485","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1296–Male":"1296–Décédé","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1415":"1415","Abt 1419":"environ 1419","1497":"1497","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1296":"1296","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","       1418":"1418","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Isabel Noel est née environ 1419, à Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Thomas Noell De Hilcott, avait 124 ans et sa mère, Jane Sounde, avait 41 ans. Elle a épousé Thomas Chetwode environ 1439, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu